               <desc>
                  <p  type="site-data" source="#bibl000048ya-2">
                  The site of the Fengsheng Monastery was thought to have originally been the residence of the Tang period general Yuchi Jingde 尉遲敬德 (d. ca. 658 CE). It was converted to a monastery in 622, under the Tang dynasty. 
                  </p>
                  <p type="site-data" source="#bibl000048ya-2">
                     “The original Fengsheng Monastery was built on a large scale with an internal hall with the 
                     <term ref="/place/000048ya1">Mountain Gate</term>
                     along the central axis of the temple, a front hall, middle hall and back hall. It also had a bell and drum loft-building and scripture preserving lou 
                     <term ref="/keyword/k000086">樓</term>
                     . Grouped together they make a procession of three courtyards. Later in history it was destroyed. Presently, the Fengsheng Monastery was rebuilt in the late 1970s. It measures east to west at 126 meters and north to south at 33 meters. Its surface area is 4158 square meters. Mainly, it is composed of the 
                     <term ref="/place/000048ya1">Mountain Gate</term>
                     , the 
                     <term ref="/place/000048ya2">Transition Grand Hall</term>
                        and the 
                     <term ref="/place/000048ya3">Mahavira Grand Hall</term>
                           . “The 
                     <term ref="/place/000048ya1">Mountain Gate</term>
                     was moved from the location of the 
                     <term ref="/place/000048ya1">Jingqing Gate</term> 
                     which was the original great gate of the monastery. 
                     <term ref="/place/000048ya1">Jingqing Gate</term>
                     was, for Jinci, the original great gate. It was built during the 
                     <term ref="/keyword/k000101">Yuan</term>
                     dynasty. It is a single-eaves hip-gable roof and, in height, is 10.5 meters. It is five bays wide and four rafters deep and maintains the style of the 
                     <term ref="/keyword/k000101">Yuan</term>
                     dynasty. The 
                     <term ref="/place/000048ya1">Mountain Gate</term>
                     was moved from the location of the
                     <term ref="/place/000048ya1">Jingqing Gate</term>
                     to its current position during the 
                     <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Qing</term>
                     Its secondary rooms are spacious, and the walls are built between the peaks and the two mountains. The grand hall's top is fired glaze from the
                     <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming </term>
                     and is of unparalleled beauty.” 
                     山门由景清门迁建于此景清门为晋祠原大门,创建于元代,单檐 歇山顶,高10.5米。面阔五间,进深四椽,总体仍保持元代风格原奉圣寺规模宏大,寺内中轴线上建有山门、前殿、中殿、后殿,还有钟、鼓楼和藏经楼,组成一座三进院落,后因历史原因损毁。现奉 圣寺重建于二十世纪七十年代末,坐西向东,东西长126米,南北宽 33米,占地面积4158平方米,主要由山门、过殿和大雄宝殿组成。 
                     山门明、次间宽敞,梢间及两山筑以墙壁。殿顶琉璃为明代烧制, 精美绝伦。 
                  </p>
